test

Class StudyGroupTest

  • java.lang.Object
    • test.StudyGroupTest

  • public abstract class StudyGroupTest
extends java.lang.Object
    This class sets up the environment to test a class we don't know the implementation of. It is only meant to be inherited from. In inherited classes, you can use the class you want to test, with StudyGroupTest.TestObject. You can as well access the "real" tested class via getImplementedClass(), but please don't use the "real" class if you can avoid it anyhow.
    Author:
    josh

      • runStatic

        protected java.lang.Object runStatic(java.lang.String methodName)

        Parameters:

        Returns:

      • runStatic

        protected java.lang.Object runStatic(java.lang.String methodName,
                         java.lang.Object argument)
        Runs a static method of the tested class that takes only one argument. If there is no static method named methodName that has object.class as only formal argument or any exception occurs while trying to run it, Assert.fail(String) will be called to output a detailed error message.
        Any passed Object that is an instance of a elementary data type class will be interpreted as an elementary data type. So you can't for example call a method that is declared as foo(Integer i) with this version of runStatic. Because if you call runStatic("foo", new Integer(3)), it will search for a static method foo(int) in your tested class.
        If this version of runStatic fails to find (or select the right} method, use runStatic(String, Object, Class).
        Parameters:
        methodName - The name of the static method you want to call.
        argument - The argument (Object) you want to pass to the method. The method will be selected based on the class of this.
        Returns:
        What the method returns. null if it was a void method.

      • runStatic

        protected java.lang.Object runStatic(java.lang.String methodName,
                         java.lang.Object argument,
                         java.lang.Class<?> argumentType)
        Runs a static method of the tested class that takes only one argument. If there is no static method named methodName that has argumentType as only formal argument or any exception occurs while trying to run it, Assert.fail(String) will be called to output a detailed error message.
        Most of the time, you don't need to use this version of runStatic, as runStatic(String, Object) does the job in 98% of all cases.
        Parameters:
        methodName - The name of the static method you want to call.
        argument - The argument you want to pass to the method.
        argumentType - The type of argument. The method will be selected based on this.
        Returns:
        What the method returns. null if it was a void method.

      • runStatic

        protected java.lang.Object runStatic(java.lang.String methodName,
                         java.lang.Object[] arguments)
        Runs a static method of the tested class that takes multiple arguments. It will select the method based the classes of the arguments. If there is no static method that is named methodName and takes the classes of arguments as formal arguments, Assert.fail(String) will be called to output a detailed error message.
        Any passed Object that is an instance of a elementary data type class will be interpreted as an elementary data type. So you can't for example call a method that is declared as foo(Integer i, Long l) with this version of runStatic. Because if you call runStatic("foo", new Object[]{new Integer(3), new Long(2L)}), it will search for a static method foo(int, long) in your tested class.
        If this method fails to find the right method in the tested class, use runStatic(String, Object[], Class[])!
        Parameters:
        methodName - The name of the static method you want to call.
        arguments - The arguments you want to pass to the method in the correct order.
        Returns:
        What the method returns. null if it was a void method.

      • runStatic

        protected java.lang.Object runStatic(java.lang.String methodName,
                         java.lang.Object[] arguments,
                         java.lang.Class<?>[] argumentTypes)
        The most generic way to call a static method of the tested class. Runs a static method that takes multiple arguments. It will search a method with the formal parameters provided in argumentTypes named methodName. If there is no such method, Assert.fail(String) will be called to output a detailed error message.
        Usually, it should not be necessary to use this method. runStatic(String, Object[]) will do the job most of the time!
        Parameters:
        methodName - The name of the static method you want to call.
        arguments - The arguments you want to pass to the method in the correct order.
        argumentTypes - The method's formal argument's classes. By them, the method will be selected.
        Returns:
        What the method returns. null if it was a void method.
